":"1229–1316","1229–1266":"1229–1266","1250–1302":"1250–1302","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1280–1295":"1280–1295","Bef 26 November 1302":"before 26 November 1302","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1302":"1302","1266":"1266","8 January 1266":"8 January 1266","1229":"1229","1317":"1317","Acton, Cheshire, England":"Acton, Cheshire, England","Fownhope, Herefordshire, England":"Fownhope, Herefordshire, England","Snodhill, Herefordshire, England":"Snodhill, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Acton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places, especially in Shropshire and adjacent counties, named Acton. Generally, these are from Old English <i>āc</i> ‘oak’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. In Ireland the surname has been established in Connacht since the 17th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":30,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","descript